00:37:15.650 --> 00:37:20.140
So the earlier
fintech, way back--

00:37:20.140 --> 00:37:22.840
I'm going to take you to a
story about an earlier fintech

00:37:22.840 --> 00:37:23.530
that I like.

00:37:23.530 --> 00:37:25.900
It's just credit cards.

00:37:25.900 --> 00:37:27.640
The first use of
the term credit card

00:37:27.640 --> 00:37:31.690
was in the 1880s
in a dystopian--

00:37:31.690 --> 00:37:33.880
I would call it, but
utopian book that

00:37:33.880 --> 00:37:35.830
was written by Edward Bellamy.

00:37:35.830 --> 00:37:37.780
It was a New York
Times bestseller.

00:37:37.780 --> 00:37:41.170
It was a bestseller in multiple
languages around the globe,

00:37:41.170 --> 00:37:43.570
talking about the year 2000.

00:37:43.570 --> 00:37:46.030
Well, Bellamy-- you could go
back and look at the book.

00:37:46.030 --> 00:37:48.010
It's really science fiction.

00:37:48.010 --> 00:37:50.890
But use the term credit card.

00:37:50.890 --> 00:37:53.020
It's the first known
use of the concept

00:37:53.020 --> 00:37:56.920
that you would have
a card for payments.

00:37:56.920 --> 00:38:00.400
Well, shortly thereafter, not
really because of Bellamy,

00:38:00.400 --> 00:38:03.880
you saw a bunch of companies
starting to use charge coins

00:38:03.880 --> 00:38:05.020
and charge cards.

00:38:05.020 --> 00:38:08.980
And by the 1920s,
these merchant cards--

00:38:08.980 --> 00:38:12.970
you had an individual merchant
providing credit and saying you

00:38:12.970 --> 00:38:14.860
can buy something on credit.

00:38:14.860 --> 00:38:17.380
You could call that a
point-of-sale credit.

00:38:17.380 --> 00:38:20.320
Earlier fintech-- about
a hundred years ago.

00:38:20.320 --> 00:38:26.230
But in the 1940s, one
banker in Brooklyn

00:38:26.230 --> 00:38:28.720
never made a lot of
money for themselves.

00:38:28.720 --> 00:38:34.900
One banker came up with the
concept of a credit system

00:38:34.900 --> 00:38:38.170
where it was multiple merchants.

00:38:38.170 --> 00:38:41.410
Not one merchant, but
multiple merchants.

00:38:41.410 --> 00:38:43.720
And that charge card--

00:38:43.720 --> 00:38:49.420
75 years ago, so a long time
ago, but still somewhat recent.

00:38:49.420 --> 00:38:52.030
And that led to
the 1940s and '50s,

00:38:52.030 --> 00:38:55.060
all these innovations--
the first plastic card.

00:38:55.060 --> 00:38:58.300
BankAmericard was from
a California bank.

00:38:58.300 --> 00:39:00.430
And that's where Visa started.

00:39:00.430 --> 00:39:03.850
So all of that was
fintech of the time.

00:39:03.850 --> 00:39:05.460
And the only reason
I mention it is

00:39:05.460 --> 00:39:08.740
if you think about what
disruptions have come before

00:39:08.740 --> 00:39:11.260
that now we take for
granted, sometimes

00:39:11.260 --> 00:39:13.960
that's evidence in
what you might do now.

00:39:13.960 --> 00:39:17.590
BankAmericard was
a California bank

00:39:17.590 --> 00:39:20.980
that was trying to partner with
other banks around the country

00:39:20.980 --> 00:39:22.480
and partnered with
other countries

00:39:22.480 --> 00:39:27.280
to do something that was more
universal for the country.

00:39:27.280 --> 00:39:30.490
The Diners Club was literally
about this restaurant concept.

00:39:30.490 --> 00:39:32.710
You would consider it almost
like a general merchant

00:39:32.710 --> 00:39:34.720
card, an early Toast.

00:39:34.720 --> 00:39:36.940
The Diners Club did
what maybe Toast

00:39:36.940 --> 00:39:39.880
is trying to do now,
inside the restaurants,

00:39:39.880 --> 00:39:45.910
providing more use of those
initially high-end restaurants

00:39:45.910 --> 00:39:46.840
on the East Coast.

00:39:49.850 --> 00:39:53.360
So what disruptions are
in the value chain now?

