they actually make?

00:55:49.810 --> 00:55:54.100
Because I'm thinking the more
and more companies we can see,

00:55:54.100 --> 00:55:55.670
the fees are going to go down.

00:55:55.670 --> 00:55:58.420
So competition will
drive their fees down.

00:55:58.420 --> 00:56:00.400
They also have to
pay a fee to-- you'd

00:56:00.400 --> 00:56:03.970
see they're a balance
sheet bank or in the case

00:56:03.970 --> 00:56:05.960
of securitization, too.

00:56:05.960 --> 00:56:07.960
GARY GENSLER: So you're
absolutely right.

00:56:07.960 --> 00:56:13.900
But financial intermediation
has multiple layers.

00:56:13.900 --> 00:56:17.860
And the more advanced
an economy is, usually

00:56:17.860 --> 00:56:19.000
the more the layers.

00:56:19.000 --> 00:56:23.440
And the more competition in
the market, more the layers.

00:56:23.440 --> 00:56:26.830
And you might think of
layers as inefficiency.

00:56:26.830 --> 00:56:28.030
It might be.

00:56:28.030 --> 00:56:31.360
But often, layers would bring
efficiency and competition.

00:56:31.360 --> 00:56:35.650
So some financial firm
is doing the origination.

00:56:35.650 --> 00:56:39.760
This is brokering and selling
and providing a user interface.

00:56:39.760 --> 00:56:42.360
And they might not want to
be the balance sheet lender.

00:56:42.360 --> 00:56:44.708
They might say, I'm going
to partner with the bank

00:56:44.708 --> 00:56:46.000
to be the balance sheet lender.

00:56:46.000 --> 00:56:48.730
What we're going to do is
we're going to compete and give

00:56:48.730 --> 00:56:52.840
the most remarkable, robust
user interface and brokerage.

00:56:52.840 --> 00:56:57.310
In the mortgage market, back to
